  \"summary\": \"Account value is the key variable in COI rate calculation\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The account value is a central variable in determining the COI rate, as the rate is based on the difference between the death benefit and the account value. A declining account value increases the difference, which in turn increases the COI rate, leading to higher monthly deductions. Conversely, a growing account value reduces the difference and may lower the COI rate. This feedback loop means that the account's performance directly impacts its long-term sustainability. Policyholders must monitor their account value closely to anticipate changes in their financial obligations [Data: Entities (41), Relationships (83)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Monthly Deduction ensures consistent financial management\",\n            \"explanation\": \"By deducting Total Charges on the 3rd of each month, the system enforces a disciplined and predictable financial rhythm. This regularity helps prevent account depletion due to irregular or missed payments. The fixed date also allows for automated processing, reducing administrative burden and minimizing human error. This structured approach supports the long-term viability of the insurance policy and provides transparency for policyholders regarding when and how their account is affected [Data: Entities (42), Relationships (86)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Total Charges serve as a consolidated financial metric\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Total Charges entity functions as a consolidated measure of all monthly deductions, combining the COI rate and administrative fees into a single value. This simplifies reporting and analysis, allowing both insurers and policyholders to track the overall cost of maintaining the policy. The aggregation also enables easier comparison across different policies or account types. By treating Total Charges as a distinct entity, the system